Q3)Display the First Three Rows
Write a solution to display the first 3 rows of this DataFrame.

.shape → attribute (not a method)
.head() → method

Value → no ()
Action → ()

       Value:
Something that already exists
Stored information
You can print it immediately
You do not tell it to do anything

Examples in pandas:
df.shape        # (rows, cols)
df.columns      # Index([...])
df.index        # RangeIndex(...)
df.dtypes       # data types
These are values. They’re just sitting there.
df.shape        # ✅
df.shape()      # ❌ (trying to “run” a value)


        Action:
Something that does work
Computes or changes data
Needs instructions
Runs when you call it
Examples in pandas:

df.head(3)
df.dropna()
df.fillna(0)
df.describe()
These are actions.
So:
df.head(3)      # ✅
df.head      

TL:DR
“Is this information about the DataFrame, or am I telling it to do something?”
Information → value → no ()
Do something → action → ()

Ans:) 
return employees.head(3)
return employees.head().iloc[:3]
Translation:
“Give me rows at positions 0, 1, 2.”

Wrong: .loc[:3]
employees.index
# [5, 7, 9, 11, 13]
Then:
.loc[:3]   # label 3 does not exist → fail
.iloc[:3] # positions 0,1,2 → works
Use .iloc for row counts
Use .loc for meaning

4)
pd.DataFrame(data, columns=[...])   # creation
df.loc[rows, columns]               # selection

students[...] is column selection only
When you do: students[...]
Pandas expects:
a column name   or a list of column names   or a boolean mask

| Task             | Correct syntax                      |
| ---------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Create DataFrame | `pd.DataFrame(data, columns=[...])` |
| Filter rows      | `df[df["col"] == value]`            |
| Select columns   | `df[["c1","c2"]]`                   |
| Filter + select  | `df.loc[rows, columns]`             |

A1) Wrong: return students.loc["student_id","name","age"]
return students.loc[students["student_id"] == 101, ["name", "age"]]

A2) Wrong: return students["student_id"] == 101[["name","age"]]
return students[students["student_id"] == 101][["name", "age"]]     and return students.loc[students.student_id == 101][["name", "age"]]  both are same

students["student_id"] == 101
This returns a Series of booleans like:
Copy code
0     True
1    False
2    False
3    False
dtype: bool
That is:
not a DataFrame
not filtered data just a mask
Why the error says “Series”
Because boolean masks are Series.
The problem explicitly wants a DataFrame.

1️⃣ Select columns only
Use this when rows don’t matter.
df["age"]                  # Series
df[["name", "age"]]        # DataFrame
Rule:
single column → Series
list of columns → DataFrame

2️⃣ Select rows only
Use this when columns don’t matter.
By position
df.iloc[:3]
df.iloc[1:5]

By condition
df[df["age"] > 18]

3️⃣ Select rows AND columns (most important)
This is the grown-up form. Learn this and stop inventing syntax.
Label-based
df.loc[ rows , columns ]
Example:
df.loc[df["student_id"] == 101, ["name", "age"]]

Position-based
df.iloc[ rows , columns ]
Example:
df.iloc[:3, [1, 2]]

